For this, we will determine the NPV of the project with the new machine. The NPV or the net present value can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Net present value}&=\text{Present value cash flow}-\text{Initial investment}\\
&-\text{Net working capital}
\end{aligned}$$

To get the present value cash flow, we will first get the operating cash flow. The operating cash flow can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Operating cash flow}&=\text{Savings} \times(1-\text{Tax rate})\\
&+\text{Tax rate} \times \text{Depreciation}
\end{aligned}$$

The present value for the operating cash flow can be solved using this formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value cash flow}&=\dfrac{\text{OCF of Year 1}-\text{Net working capital of Year 1}}{(1+0.09)^1}+\dfrac{\text{OCF of Year 2}-\text{Net working capital of Year 2}}{(1+0.09)^2}\\
&+\dfrac{\text{OCF of Year 3}-\text{Net working capital of Year 3}}{(1+0.09)^3}+\dfrac{\text{OCF of Year 4}+\text{Net working capital of Year 4}+\text{After-tax salvage value}}{(1+0.09)^4}
\end{aligned}$$
